<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="371" pageId="3" pageNumber="370" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1747,2024]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="371" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1857" box="[151,359,1747,1772]" class="Anthozoa" family="Antipathidae" genus="Antipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="3" pageNumber="370" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="furcata">
<emphasis box="[151,359,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Antipathes furcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms fan-shaped colonies that are typically less than 
<quantity box="[977,1047,1747,1772]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="370" unit="cm" value="50.0">50 cm</quantity>
in height, with long branches that grow in narrow branch angles (
<figureCitation box="[523,668,1783,1808]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[182,1393,327,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[182,1402,327,1202]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antipathes furcata from Bermuda showing (a) colony in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on terminal branch under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on terminal branch under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 10 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042992/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figure 2a–b</figureCitation>
). The terminal branches typically reach lengths of 
<quantity box="[1272,1332,1783,1808]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="370" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
or more without becoming branched. Skeletal spines are smooth, triangular or slightly inclined distally, and occasionally include some that are bifurcated towards their apex (
<figureCitation box="[746,860,1855,1880]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[182,1393,327,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[182,1402,327,1202]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antipathes furcata from Bermuda showing (a) colony in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on terminal branch under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on terminal branch under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 10 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042992/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figure 2d</figureCitation>
). The spines are generally 30–70 µm in height and typically 50–70 µm in width at their base. On smaller branches, the spines are arranged in axial rows with adjoining rows offset in a spiral pattern around the corallum (
<figureCitation box="[726,839,1927,1952]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[182,1393,327,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[182,1402,327,1202]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antipathes furcata from Bermuda showing (a) colony in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on terminal branch under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on terminal branch under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 10 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042992/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figure 2d</figureCitation>
). Spine spacing is fairly regular within each row, and typically ranges between 240–280 µm. The polyps are arranged on only one side of the branches, are generally 0.6– 1.0 mm in transverse diameter, and are spaced 
<quantity box="[699,837,2000,2024]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="370" unit="mm" value="1.2" valueMax="1.3" valueMin="1.1">1.1–1.3 mm</quantity>
apart (
<figureCitation box="[920,1034,1999,2024]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[182,1393,327,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[182,1402,327,1202]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antipathes furcata from Bermuda showing (a) colony in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on terminal branch under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on terminal branch under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 10 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042992/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figure 2c</figureCitation>
). The coloration of living colonies ranges between grayish brown to white. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1857" box="[631,746,152,176]" class="Anthozoa" family="Antipathidae" genus="Antipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="furcata">
<emphasis box="[631,746,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="371">A. furcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has previously been reported from the Caribbean, Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[151,236,188,213]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="371">
<collectingCountry box="[151,236,188,213]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="371">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
and North Atlantic at depths ranging between 
<quantity box="[800,918,188,213]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.775" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="0.15" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" unit="m" value="177.5" valueMax="340.0" valueMin="15.0">15–340 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brito" box="[937,1191,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" refString="Brito, A. &amp; Ocana, O. (2004) Corales de las Islas Canarias: antozoos con esqueleto de los fondos litorales y profundos. La Laguna, Tenerife, 475 pp." type="book" year="2004">Brito &amp; Ocaña, 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cairns" box="[1208,1431,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" refString="Cairns, S. D., Opresko, D. M. &amp; Hopkins, T. S. (1993) New records of deep-water Cnidaria (Scleractinia &amp; Antipatharia) from the Gulf of Mexico. Northeast Gulf Science, 13, 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="1993">
Cairns 
<emphasis box="[1292,1353,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="371">et al.</emphasis>
, 1993
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[151,321,223,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" refString="Opresko, D. M. (2009) Antipatharia (Cnidaria) of the Gulf of Mexico. In: Tunnell, J. W. Jr., Felder, D. L. &amp; Earle, S. A. (Eds.), Gulf of Mexico origin, waters, and biota. Vol. 1. Biodiversity. Texas A &amp; M University Press, Corpus Christi, 359 - 363." type="book chapter" year="2009">Opresko, 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[334,571,223,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" refString="Opresko, D. M., Nuttall, M. F. &amp; Hickerson, E. L. (2016) Black corals of the Flower Garden Banks National Marine Sanctuary. Gulf of Mexico Science Science, 2016, 47 - 67." type="journal article" year="2016">
Opresko 
<emphasis box="[438,496,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="371">et al.</emphasis>
, 2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[585,889,223,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" refString="Opresko, D. M. &amp; Sanchez, J. A. (2005) Caribbean shallow-water black corals (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Antipatharia). Caribbean Journal of Science, 41, 492 - 507." type="journal article" year="2005">Opresko &amp; Sanchez, 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Bermudan specimens examined as part of this study were collected at depths between 
<quantity box="[596,709,260,285]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.04" metricValueMin="0.96" pageId="4" pageNumber="371" unit="m" value="100.0" valueMax="104.0" valueMin="96.0">96–104 m</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[723,806,260,285]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,440,463]" captionText="TABLE 1. Black coral specimens examined as part of this study (BAMZ = Bermuda Aquarium, Museum and Zoo; NR = not reported; * = new record for Bermuda)." pageId="4" pageNumber="371">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
